-cliche

For our latest commissioned essay, Catherine Shannon turns a writer=E2=80=
=99s taboo on its head.
All writers agree: clich=C3=A9s are to be avoided, mercilessly scrubbed out=
 of our prose with boiling hot water and steel wool. Ideally, we burn ourse=
lves a bit in the process as punishment for putting them there in the first=
 place. (Should clich=C3=A9s be avoided like the plague? Probably. Is that =
itself a clich=C3=A9? Yes.)
=E2=80=9CBad writing relies heavily on ready-made phrases,=E2=80=9D writes =
Christopher Lasch in his style guide, Plain Style. =E2=80=9CThis method of =
writing requires less effort than original thought, but it provides readers=
 with neither delight nor instruction.=E2=80=9D And that=E2=80=99s just it=
=E2=80=94what we hate most about a clich=C3=A9 in prose is its sheer lazine=
ss, coupled with its shameless presentation as extraordinary or original th=
ought.
Even so, if clich=C3=A9s are phrases or ideas so overused that they=E2=80=
=99ve lost their meaning, whose fault is that? Arguably not the clich=C3=A9=
=E2=80=99s. As Jack Hanson notes in the Cleveland Review of Books, one coul=
d make the case that strong writing eventually devolves into clich=C3=A9. A=
 turn of phrase so powerful that it encourages imitation is admirable; perh=
aps it is the task of the writer to come up with a few clich=C3=A9s of her =
own. That said, it=E2=80=99s far too easy, as a writer, to think of oneself=
 as an utterly original voice, to confuse novelty with genius, when the tru=
th is closer to how T.S. Eliot put it: =E2=80=9CNo poet, no artist of any a=
rt, has his complete meaning alone.=E2=80=9D
To be clear on where I stand: I will never defend clich=C3=A9s in prose=E2=
=80=94a quizzical brow, a deafening silence, endless possibilities, or even=
 a bright blue sky. What I will defend is opening our hearts to the clich=
=C3=A9s of life.
There=E2=80=99s a big difference between clich=C3=A9d writing and clich=C3=
=A9d wisdom. While certain sayings that feel clich=C3=A9d to us may be worn=
 thin, they are not lazy strings of overused words. They are idioms, metaph=
ors, proverbs, or aphorisms, and, taken together, they form a kind of commo=
n wisdom worthy of defense. =E2=80=9CIf it ain=E2=80=99t broke, don=E2=80=
=99t fix it.=E2=80=9D Funny and true. =E2=80=9CEasy come, easy go.=E2=80=9D=
 Alas. =E2=80=9CNo man ever steps in the same river twice.=E2=80=9D Profoun=
d. There is more wisdom on Pinterest, set in that insufferable millennial w=
edding font, than many writers would care to admit. =E2=80=9CTime will tell=
=2E=E2=80=9D Indeed, it will.
So much for wisdom. We also shouldn=E2=80=99t avoid clich=C3=A9d experience=
s. As our lives increasingly lose touch with everyday experiences in the re=
al world, perhaps we should aim to have more of them (the everyday experien=
ces, I mean). We live in a world riddled with disaffected irony [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/99c71cfa-1fc4-4a9f-8a63-81d7c0fc8da9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ=
29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]. Social media rewards =
the unusual, the exaggerated, the hysterical, the false; it=E2=80=99s why w=
e=E2=80=99re bombarded with bizarre things like elderflower cappuccinos. To=
o often, clich=C3=A9d experiences are maligned for being =E2=80=9Cbasic=E2=
=80=9D when they=E2=80=99re actually just normal (and often quite good). A =
secure person can unironically enjoy a pumpkin spice latte. If you=E2=80=99=
re on page 37 of the SSENSE sale, you may never know the happiness of going=
 to Target to get some fall candles. But I hope you do. (I hope we all do.)=
 Red roses for Valentine=E2=80=99s Day? Well, what were you hoping for inst=
ead? A bunch of snapdragons? I would encourage all of us, especially the di=
saffected urbanites reading this, not to nibble around the edges of life bu=
t to devour it, to take in its most foundational and clich=C3=A9d experienc=
es without irony or reservation.
In our competitive, status-driven, and materialistic society, we all rely t=
oo much on commodities and experiences to provide us with meaning instead o=
f what we bring to any given thing or experience. This is why 20-somethings=
 on a thrifting budget will always look cooler than some advertising execut=
ive who wears the latest designer trends head-to-toe. (The 20-something wea=
rs the clothes; the clothes wear the advertising executive.) When I became =
a mother last year, it was liberating to simply realize that I can be a mom=
 in my own way. I don=E2=80=99t have to take on every clich=C3=A9d associat=
ion I=E2=80=99ve ever had with motherhood, view it as a monolith, or weigh =
it down with leaden expectations. My experience of motherhood hasn=E2=80=99=
t been without hardship or sacrifice, of course (no one=E2=80=99s is), but =
it has felt a bit lighter. Had I deeply internalized a singular, clich=C3=
=A9d idea of motherhood, I may have missed out entirely on the joyful clich=
=C3=A9 of becoming one.
When we feel alienated, it=E2=80=99s easy to double down, go further down t=
he path of needless novelties and obscurities=E2=80=94like Des Esseintes in=
 =C3=80 Rebours=E2=80=94to rarefy our tastes and appetites beyond the point=
 of parody, attempt to further distinguish and separate ourselves from othe=
rs. But these small sips of status never quite quench our thirst, and a ret=
urn to basics is sometimes required. So-called clich=C3=A9s, whether in wis=
dom or in experience, are easily understood; they tie us to one another, an=
d they clearly endure. Clich=C3=A9s are not intellectual or aesthetic crime=
s, but grounded, commonplace truths, repeated endlessly. When we dismiss cl=
ich=C3=A9s outright, we risk dismissing the common life they articulate. Sp=
oken with love, the most familiar words remind us that we are not so alone =
in this life; they place our private sorrows and joys in the shared custody=
 of language. As we parents love to say to one another, and to anyone who w=
ill listen: all the clich=C3=A9s are true.

