x;margin: 32px 0;text-align: center;font-weight: 500;font-style: italic;">F=
or our latest commissioned essay, Catherine Shannon turns a writer&#8217;s =
taboo on its head.</p></div><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55=
,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>All writers agree: clich&#23=
3;s are to be avoided, mercilessly scrubbed out of our prose with boiling h=
ot water and steel wool. Ideally, we burn ourselves a bit in the process as=
 punishment for putting them there in the first place. (Should clich&#233;s=
 be avoided</span><em> like the plague</em><span>? Probably. Is that itself=
 a clich&#233;? Yes.)</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(5=
4,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>&#8220;Bad writing relie=
s heavily on ready-made phrases,&#8221; writes Christopher Lasch in his sty=
le guide, </span><em>Plain Style</em><span>. &#8220;This method of writing =
requires less effort than original thought, but it provides readers with ne=
ither delight nor instruction.&#8221; And that&#8217;s just it&#8212;what w=
e hate most about a clich&#233; in prose is its sheer laziness, coupled wit=
h its shameless presentation as extraordinary or original thought.</span></=
p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;fon=
t-size: 16px;"><span>Even so, if clich&#233;s are phrases or ideas so overu=
sed that they&#8217;ve lost their meaning, whose fault is that? Arguably no=
t the clich&#233;&#8217;s. As Jack Hanson notes in the </span><em>Cleveland=
 Review of Books</em><span>, one could make the case that strong writing ev=
entually devolves into clich&#233;. A turn of phrase so powerful that it en=
courages imitation is admirable; perhaps it is the task of the writer to co=
me up with a few clich&#233;s of her own. That said, it&#8217;s far too eas=
y, as a writer, to think of oneself as an utterly original voice, to confus=
e novelty with genius, when the truth is closer to how T.S. Eliot put it: &=
#8220;No poet, no artist of any art, has his complete meaning alone.&#8221;=
</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height:=
 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>To be clear on where I stand: I will never de=
fend clich&#233;s in prose&#8212;a </span><em>quizzical brow</em><span>, a =
</span><em>deafening silence</em><span>, </span><em>endless possibilities</=
em><span>, or even a </span><em>bright blue sky</em><span>. What I will def=
end is opening our hearts to the clich&#233;s of life.</span></p><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16=
px;"><span>There&#8217;s a big difference between clich&#233;d writing and =
clich&#233;d wisdom. While certain sayings that feel clich&#233;d to us may=
 be worn thin, they are not lazy strings of overused words. They are idioms=
, metaphors, proverbs, or aphorisms, and, taken together, they form a kind =
of common wisdom worthy of defense. </span><em>&#8220;If it ain&#8217;t bro=
ke, don&#8217;t fix it.&#8221;</em><span> Funny and true. </span><em>&#8220=
;Easy come, easy go.&#8221;</em><span> Alas. </span><em>&#8220;No man ever =
steps in the same river twice.&#8221;</em><span> Profound. There is more wi=
sdom on Pinterest, set in that insufferable millennial wedding font, than m=
any writers would care to admit.</span><em> &#8220;Time will tell.&#8221; <=
/em><span>Indeed, it will.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: =
rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>So much for wisdom.=
 We also shouldn&#8217;t avoid clich&#233;d </span><em>experiences</em><spa=
n>. As our lives increasingly lose touch with everyday experiences in the r=
eal world, perhaps we should aim to have more of them (the everyday experie=
nces, I mean). We live in a world riddled with disaffected </span><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/99c71cfa-1fc4-4a9f-8a63-81d7c0fc8da9?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys" rel=3D"" s=
tyle=3D"color: #ff7731;text-decoration: none;">irony</a><span>. Social medi=
a rewards the unusual, the exaggerated, the hysterical, the false; it&#8217=
;s why we&#8217;re bombarded with bizarre things like elderflower cappuccin=
os. Too often, clich&#233;d experiences are maligned for being &#8220;basic=
&#8221; when they&#8217;re actually just normal (and often quite good). A s=
ecure person can unironically enjoy a pumpkin spice latte. If you&#8217;re =
on page 37 of the SSENSE sale, you may never know the happiness of going to=
 Target to get some fall candles. But I hope you do. (I hope we all do.) Re=
d roses for Valentine&#8217;s Day? Well, what were you hoping for instead? =
A bunch of snapdragons? I would encourage all of us, especially the disaffe=
cted urbanites reading this, not to nibble around the edges of life but to =
devour it, to take in its most foundational and clich&#233;d experiences wi=
thout irony or reservation.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color:=
 rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>In our competitive=
, status-driven, and materialistic society, we all rely too much on commodi=
ties and experiences to provide us with meaning instead of what </span><em>=
we bring to any given thing or experience. </em><span>This is why 20-someth=
ings on a thrifting budget will always look cooler than some advertising ex=
ecutive who wears the latest designer trends head-to-toe. (The 20-something=
 wears the clothes; the clothes wear the advertising executive.) When I bec=
ame a mother last year, it was liberating to simply realize that I can be a=
 mom in my own way. I don&#8217;t have to take on every clich&#233;d associ=
ation I&#8217;ve ever had with motherhood, view it as a monolith, or weigh =
it down with leaden expectations. My experience of motherhood hasn&#8217;t =
been without hardship or sacrifice, of course (no one&#8217;s is), but it h=
as felt a bit lighter. Had I deeply internalized a singular, clich&#233;d i=
dea of motherhood, I may have missed out entirely on the joyful clich&#233;=
 of becoming one.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55=
,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>When we feel alienated, it&#=
8217;s easy to double down, go further down the path of needless novelties =
and obscurities&#8212;like Des Esseintes in </span><em>&#192; Rebours</em><=
span>&#8212;to rarefy our tastes and appetites beyond the point of parody, =
attempt to further distinguish and separate ourselves from others. But thes=
e small sips of status never quite quench our thirst, and a return to basic=
s is sometimes required. So-called clich&#233;s, whether in wisdom or in ex=
perience, are easily understood; they tie us to one another, and they clear=
ly endure</span><em>. </em><span>Clich&#233;s are not intellectual or aesth=
etic crimes, but grounded, commonplace truths, repeated endlessly. When we =
dismiss clich&#233;s outright, we risk dismissing the common life they arti=
culate. Spoken with love, the most familiar words remind us that we are not=
 so alone in this life; they place our private sorrows and joys in the shar=
ed custody of language. As we parents love to say to one another, and to an=
yone who will listen: </span><em>all the clich&#233;s are true.</em></p><di=
